{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS-1 REVIEW (G6 — approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection) on the repo-snapshot-isolation plan (\"Repo-snapshot isolation for code-reading gates\"). Grounded against src/rebar/signing.py, _commands/transition.py, llm/completion.py.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (criteria this chunk passes):\n- G6 mechanism (snapshot path): the core mechanism — read content from the object store WITHOUT a worktree, pin an immutable SHA, atomic dir-rename population + single-flight + delete-on-last-close, reaper + free-space cap — is logically complete and its concurrency/atomicity story is sound and standard. The explicit rejection of `git archive` (lossy) in favor of `read-tree`+`checkout-index` (faithful) is a correct correctness call.\n- G6 fitness-for-purpose: the attested/local split structurally bars the named footgun (local mode \"NEVER sign\"; \"structurally barred from producing a signed verdict\") — this directly solves the false-negative-on-wrong-branch incident, not a proxy.\n- G6 alternative-selection: the chosen object-store-materialization approach is defensibly at-least-as-good vs. the obvious structural alternative (`git worktree add` per snapshot) on lock-contention/blast-radius — the plan's \"no worktrees\" choice is the better one and is grounded.\n- G6 positive rationale: present — \"grounded against mainstream practice (Gitaly, Sourcegraph gitserver/zoekt, GitHub tarball API, Bazel, ccache, Nix, in-toto)… match what those systems ship.\" Satisfies the positive-rationale requirement (no rejected-alternatives section required).\n\nFINDINGS:\n\n- [ ] [G6 — mechanism correctness, load-bearing seam] The plan asserts the attested mode will \"record `verified_at_sha` on the ticket and SIGN over it. Reproducible\" and AC2 requires a signed verdict to be \"bound to `verified_at_sha`\" — but the EXISTING signing mechanism deliberately does the opposite. `src/rebar/signing.py` signs only the canonical payload `{v, algorithm, ticket_id, manifest}` (`_canonical_payload`, lines 188-201) and records `head_sha` as AUDIT METADATA ONLY, by explicit design: \"The signed payload deliberately does NOT include volatile git state, so a signature stays certifiable as the repo evolves (head_sha is recorded as audit metadata only)\" (docstring lines 19-25). So as written, a SHA recorded on the ticket is NOT cryptographically bound to the signature — re-signing/tampering the SHA field would still verify `certified`. To actually BIND `verified_at_sha` into the signature (AC2's \"bound to\"), the SHA must enter the signed payload, which forces (a) a `PAYLOAD_VERSION` bump that INVALIDATES every prior signature, and (b) changes to `sign_manifest` / `compute_signature` / `verify_record` and the close-gate signing call site (`_commands/transition.py:396`, which today signs only `verified_manifest`). The plan does not name this integration point, does not acknowledge the design tension with the existing \"exclude volatile git state\" decision, and does not specify whether prior signatures are migrated/orphaned. This is the load-bearing reproducibility claim, so under-specifying it risks the implementer either (i) only recording an unbound SHA field (fails AC2's \"bound to\"/\"reproducible\") or (ii) silently invalidating all existing certified closures. Please specify the binding mechanism and the prior-signature consequence.\n  - location: \"## What\" → attested bullet (\"record verified_at_sha on the ticket and SIGN over it. Reproducible\"); Acceptance Criteria line 2 (\"A signed verdict records verified_at_sha and is reproducible … bound to verified_at_sha\"); src/rebar/signing.py:19-25,188-201; src/rebar/_commands/transition.py:393-396\n  - suggested_fix: State explicitly HOW the SHA is bound. The lowest-blast-radius option that needs NO payload-version bump and NO prior-signature invalidation: thread `verified_at_sha` into the verified-step MANIFEST itself (e.g. a canonical step string `\"verified_at_sha: <sha>\"`), so it enters the already-signed `manifest` field via the existing `sign_manifest(ticket_id, manifest)` path unchanged — the SHA is then cryptographically bound and reproducible with zero change to the signing payload schema. If instead you want a first-class `verified_at_sha` payload field, the plan must own the `PAYLOAD_VERSION` bump + the \"all prior signatures become non-certifiable\" migration consequence and say so in scope.\n\n- [ ] [G6 — alternative-selection, possibly-simpler missed path] Related to the above: the plan presents binding-the-SHA as if it requires a new signing surface, but a structurally-different, codebase-aligned alternative exists — bind the SHA through the EXISTING manifest channel rather than extending the signed payload. Since `sign_manifest`/`verify_record` already sign the full manifest and the close gate already produces `verified_manifest`, carrying the SHA as a manifest step is smaller blast-radius (no schema/version change, no prior-signature breakage) and equally reproducible. Coaching only: have the plan consider this manifest-channel binding before committing to a payload-schema change, and state which it chose and why.\n  - location: \"## What\" attested bullet; src/rebar/signing.py:160-206 (parse_manifest / compute_signature already sign the manifest); src/rebar/_commands/transition.py:362-396 (verified_manifest is the existing signing input)\n  - suggested_fix: (empty — defer to the planner's choice; the prior finding's suggested_fix sketches the manifest-channel option)\n\nEverything else in the approach (snapshot materialization, concurrency model, portability, local/attested separation) is sound and well-specified for G6. The two findings both converge on a single seam: how exactly the pinned SHA becomes part of the SIGNED (not merely recorded) attestation."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782519564926374001,"uuid":"edebb80f-039a-4cc0-aa51-663dc7c8fb3e"}